              <span id="reviewTextContainer3009455340" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12527484781923523020">I knew when finishing Relic I needed to jump into this book ASAP. I had nothing to base this book off like I did with book one-having seen the movie. (While the basic outline was the same enough details were changed really making the book stand out on its own.) The suspense, mystery and intrigue in this book was just as powerful as the first book. I struggled with putting this book down as the suspense just escalated as the story went on. While book one floored me with the inner workings of the </span>
  <span id="freeText12527484781923523020" style="display:none">I knew when finishing Relic I needed to jump into this book ASAP. I had nothing to base this book off like I did with book one-having seen the movie. (While the basic outline was the same enough details were changed really making the book stand out on its own.) The suspense, mystery and intrigue in this book was just as powerful as the first book. I struggled with putting this book down as the suspense just escalated as the story went on. While book one floored me with the inner workings of the museum, this time the vastness and complexity of the NY underground took center stage. We find out the end result of Greg stealing away with the infamous plant and manipulating the virus and thinking he could control it. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[The bomb about Dr. Frock really threw me for a loop and I’m actually more impressed with the authors skill in weaving such a complex story. I really didn’t see Frock being involved but in a sick way it works for the story, especially his why. I also enjoyed the ritualistic and anthropological details used as a way to control and manipulate. The hut built from all the skulls and used as a way for Frock to take on a god like status was fascinating and sad.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> <br />I really loved the gang getting back together and from start to finish I was sucked in to the story. It also served as a harsh reminder from things like of the living conditions of the homeless to the power of the rich. I loved how the book started with a dive in shit, literally. Dirty jobs exist and this was a harsh reminder why most of us put these things out of our minds, unfortunately somebodies got to do it. I was totally creeped out throughout this book. Just the thought of being so far underground to being surrounded in the pitch black and by beings both human and not who are accustomed to the dark left me with the heebie jeebies. I also think I’m enjoying this Pendergast and his vast supply of inane knowledge and random facts. He’s also braver than all hell. Him choosing to visit D’gosta for the first time after eighteen months decked out in his “homeless” finest was a clincher for me lol. I do wish we knew more about him though. Even with his being an FBI agent, he seems to have a lot of singular power, he never has a partner, seems to work on his own ‘missions’ and was able to blow up NYC tunnels with little to no pushback. My one complaint was the end, sure situations were resolved but personally I could have done with more detail on the after effects particularly for a few side characters including The police Chief and Captain Miller. Also I thought there’d be another government agency coming in like book one and taking all the evidence from the plants to whatever remains flushed out of the sewers. Hopefully there was nothing left worth taking, wouldn’t want someone else to get the same dumb idea.🤷🏼‍♀️ Loved this book and looking forward to where the series goes off to next.<br /><br />***2021 Review*** Upgrade to 4.5 Stars from 4<br />Since finishing this book for the first time last year I knew then I wanted to reread it again already. There’s just something so fascinating and mysterious about the underground in NYC. To think in a place filled with millions of people that there is a whole undiscovered and unmapped world beneath is mindblowing. 🤯🤯🤯 Not to mention that thousands of people not only live down there but raise families down there as well. While the book is fiction and only uses the abandoned tunnels etc. as a setting for the book and a place for the ‘monsters’ to hide I still love that a lot of it is based on historical truth and facts. <br />The book picked up a year after the ending of Relic. The group has lost contact and most are trying to put the museum incident behind them. They belive the beast, the virus and the death is done and over with. Only something is going on down in the tunnels that’s connected to happenings at the museum and it’s so bad (like Scooby Doo) the gang had to get back together to break it all down and put a stop to it. The irony is that in fact these mysterious deaths have been going on throughout the year but it isn’t until a socialite is murdered that anything is taken seriously. <br />I loved meeting Lieutenant Hayward again, she’s such a brilliant and undervalued character. She appears later in the series as a captain herself and she’s more than deserving of that role. Without her knowledge and assistance here I don’t think they’d have been able to figure it all out or at least not nearly as quickly. <br />The only thing I didn’t like was once again the ending. The entire final quarter of the book is so much buildup and action you are literally on the edge of your seat. I was ready, pumped and psyched to watch it all blow up in their faces. However once again when the climax hits we get a chapter end and then it’s followed up by a rehash of events after the fact. Ughhhh this is so annoying to me. Don’t just put up a wall while things are moving at 100 mph, it’s just plain mean lol. It took some of the excitement and certainly much of the thrill out of it and that was a bummer. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I was once again broken hearted when Frock is revealed as the baddie. I blame the movie because I’m so in love with his character from the film, he’s the one person I root for and even knowing he was behind all this is painful. There’s a scene in the film where the beast is outside a fenced in area he’s hiding in and the moment is tense and equally heartbreaking because even knowing he’s about to die, Frock stares eye to eye with the beast and actually smiles. He’s thrilled beyond belief not only to see his theory of evolution real and in the flesh but just so honored, if you will, to die by its hands. He’s also even in the book just the type of character you can kind of understand. He finds a cure to his polio that kept him refined to his wheelchair and now has a new chance of life. In some respects it’s understandable even if his methods were off and his execution with the monsters and plans were a bit shall we say villainous!  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> This made for a great read the second time around and I’m even thinking of rereading Cabinet of Curiousities, the first three books of the series have by far been the best and I’d highly recommend ppl at least read those as it’ll bring knowledgeable joy to any nerd who reads them, maybe a few chills and thrills as well.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12527484781923523020" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


