        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3379374345" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3039589760624217815">Reliquary is the follow up to Relic and the second Pendergast novel, it builds on the first book, there were a lot of familiar cast members and the story often refers back to Relic. I didn’t think the story was as good as Relic though.<br/><br/>Two mutilated bodies are found under water near Manhattan and Margo Green is asked to help with the investigation. Lieutenant D’Agosta is there again as well as agent Pendergast to see what is going on and to solve this one they have to look to underground New York</span>
  <span id="freeText3039589760624217815" style="display:none">Reliquary is the follow up to Relic and the second Pendergast novel, it builds on the first book, there were a lot of familiar cast members and the story often refers back to Relic. I didn’t think the story was as good as Relic though.<br /><br />Two mutilated bodies are found under water near Manhattan and Margo Green is asked to help with the investigation. Lieutenant D’Agosta is there again as well as agent Pendergast to see what is going on and to solve this one they have to look to underground New York.<br /><br />The setting for most of the book is interesting, subterranean New York and its denizens. Some parts down deep in the tunnels were pretty interesting, especially when considering they were based on actually existing places. But the book didn’t hold my attention at all times, the plot seemed a bit far fetched to me, and as a whole it was too dependent on the first book. I do like Pendergast as a main character, so I will definitely continue the series.</span>
